<h2>What's the format of Joule URLs?</h2>
<p>First, either
<ul>
<li><code>http://marnanel.org/joule</code> for HTML (a "page"), or</li>
<li><code>http://marnanel.org/joule-as-rss</code> for RSS (a
"feed").</li>
</ul>

That can be all, but you usually want to add parameters. Put a <code>?</code>
before the first one and an <code>&amp;</code> before all the others. Order
doesn't matter.

<ul>
<li><code>user=<i>name</i></code> for the username (otherwise you get the front
page)</li>
<li><code>site=<i>site</i></code> for the site code (go <a
href="/writing/joule-sites">here for the full list</a>; defaults to
<code>lj</code>)</li>
<li><code>full=1</code> for the full listing; otherwise it will only be the
last 30 days. This is ignored for RSS, which is always the last 30 days.
Be warned that this may crash your browser in graph mode if your computer
is not terribly speedy.</li>
<li><code>noblanks=1</code> to filter out blank lines (when nobody friended or
unfriended you at all). This is especially useful for RSS, because you might
not want to be told on a day when this happens.</li>
<li><code>mode=chart</code> (the default) or <code>mode=graph</code> : this should
be obvious. If not, play with Joule for five minutes.</li>
<li><code>format=html</code> (the default) or <code>format=rss</code> will
override the <code>-as-rss</code> part of the name above.</li>
<li><code>nohiccup=1</code> to remove the "hiccup" filter: see below.</li>
<li><code>dummy=<i>date</i></code> doesn't actually do anything. <a
href="/writing/weird-problems-in-programming">Certain RSS clients require
each post to have a unique URL</a> (even though <a href="http://feedvalidator.org/docs/rss2.html">the
specification</a> doesn't). Since all the entries refer to the
"most recent" page, it makes sense to have them all point to it, but
we set "dummy" to the date of each post.</li>
</ul>

